WHAT IS THIS KINGDOM
The domain that defines the physical transformation of light into
electronic signal inside a digital image sensor. It covers photon
statistics, the complete sensor noise model, exposure theory, ISO
sensitivity definitions, dual native ISO architecture, sensor
metrology parameters, and the geometric invariance required for
accurate measurement. It is the bridge between the optical image
formed by the lens and the digital RAW file.

WHY IT EXISTS
Every downstream color transform and noise reduction algorithm
depends on an accurate model of the sensor's response to light.
Without this kingdom, SNR calculations, dynamic range claims, and
exposure decisions are arbitrary. It provides the mathematical
proof for why a sensor behaves as it does, enabling consistent
RAW processing across all camera bodies and the correct design
of IDTs and noise management strategies.

HOW IT IS STRUCTURED
Seven sub-domains: Photon Statistics, Sensor Noise Model, Exposure
Theory, ISO Sensitivity and Dual Native ISO, Sensor Metrology,
Photometric and Radiometric Unit Reference, and Geometric Invariance.
Each sub-domain provides the primary equations, their domain of
validity, and explicit links to the relevant ISO and SMPTE standards.

WHERE IT IS APPLIED
RAW linearization, black level subtraction, exposure index selection
on set, digital ISO calibration, dual native ISO crossover point
calculation, sensor performance benchmarking (QE, FWC, DR), noise
profiling for denoising algorithms, and radiometric camera
calibration for machine vision and VFX.

WHO USES IT
Camera engineers, RAW decoder developers, DITs, color scientists,
and pipeline TDs who need to linearize sensor data and understand
noise characteristics.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Replaces manufacturer marketing claims with auditable, formula-based
